    <item>
      <title>ADT as a generic interface</title>
      <link>https://unibz-oofp-25-26.github.io/docs/abstractdatatypes/sections/collection/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://unibz-oofp-25-26.github.io/docs/abstractdatatypes/sections/collection/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;adt-as-a-generic-interface&#34;&gt;&#xA;  ADT as a generic interface&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#adt-as-a-generic-interface&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;An ADT in Java is usually a &lt;a href=&#34;%7b%7b%22../generics/sections/generics.md#genericType%22%7d%7d&#34;&gt;generic type&lt;/a&gt;, meaning that it accepts one or several types as parameter(s).&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote class=&#34;book-hint info&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Example.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&#xA;A list of integers has type &lt;code&gt;List&amp;lt;Integer&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote class=&#34;book-hint warning&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Syntax.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&#xA;The type &lt;code&gt;List&amp;lt;E&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; is a &lt;a href=&#34;https://unibz-oofp-25-26.github.io/docs/generic/&#34;&gt;generic type&lt;/a&gt;, with &lt;a href=&#34;https://unibz-oofp-25-26.github.io/docs/generic/sections/variable/&#34;&gt;type variable&lt;/a&gt; &lt;code&gt;E&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote class=&#34;book-hint info&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Note.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&#xA;&lt;code&gt;List&amp;lt;E&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; in Java is analogous to &lt;a href=&#34;https://unibz-oofp-25-26.github.io/docs/generic/sections/generic_type/#haskell&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;[a]&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/a&gt; in Haskell.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote class=&#34;book-hint warning&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Constraint.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&#xA;In Java, a primitive type (like &lt;code&gt;int&lt;/code&gt; or &lt;code&gt;bool&lt;/code&gt;) &lt;em&gt;cannot&lt;/em&gt; be a type parameter.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>List</title>
      <link>https://unibz-oofp-25-26.github.io/docs/abstractdatatypes/sections/list/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://unibz-oofp-25-26.github.io/docs/abstractdatatypes/sections/list/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;list&#34;&gt;&#xA;  List&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#list&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote class=&#34;book-hint warning&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The abstract data type &lt;strong&gt;list&lt;/strong&gt; simulates a finite &lt;a href=&#34;https://unibz-oofp-25-26.github.io/docs/background/sections/set_list/#list&#34;&gt;list&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Accordingly, a list may contain &lt;em&gt;duplicates&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A list may expose the following methods:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;&lt;strong&gt;isEmpty&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rdquo; is self-explanatory,&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;&lt;strong&gt;append&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rdquo; adds an element at the end of the list,&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;&lt;strong&gt;prepend&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rdquo; adds an element at the beginning of the list,&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;&lt;strong&gt;tail&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rdquo; returns the sub-list identical to the current one, but without its first element,&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;etc.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote class=&#34;book-hint info&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Note.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; The length of a list is usually unbounded (as opposed to the length of an array).&#xA;This can be implemented in different ways, for instance with a &lt;a href=&#34;https://unibz-oofp-25-26.github.io/notreleased/&#34;&gt;dynamic array&lt;/a&gt; or a &lt;a href=&#34;https://unibz-oofp-25-26.github.io/notreleased/&#34;&gt;linked list&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Set</title>
      <link>https://unibz-oofp-25-26.github.io/docs/abstractdatatypes/sections/set/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://unibz-oofp-25-26.github.io/docs/abstractdatatypes/sections/set/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;set&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Set&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#set&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote class=&#34;book-hint warning&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The abstract data type &lt;strong&gt;set&lt;/strong&gt; simulates a (usually finite) &lt;a href=&#34;https://unibz-oofp-25-26.github.io/docs/background/sections/set_list/#set&#34;&gt;set&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A set may expose the following methods:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;&lt;strong&gt;add&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;rdquo; adds an element to the set if it was not present already (and returns true iff this was the case),&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;&lt;strong&gt;contains&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;rdquo; checks whether an element belongs to the set,&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;&lt;strong&gt;size&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;rdquo; returns the cardinality of the set,&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;etc.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote class=&#34;book-hint danger&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Warning.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&#xA;By default, there is no guarantee on the &lt;em&gt;order&lt;/em&gt; of elements in a set.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
